  <tr>
    <td bgcolor="#99CCCC" >
    <div align="center"><font size="-1"><strong>&quot;Usually the number of chromosomes is constant in a given species, although it may vary between different species even of the same genus.&nbsp; In man the chromosome number is forty-eight....&quot;&nbsp; [<em>Human Genetics and its Social Import</em>, by S. J. Holmes (1936), p. 8.&nbsp; The illustration above appears on p. 9.]</strong></font></div>
	<div align="center">
      <strong><br>
      <font size="-1">&quot;... the number of chromosomes is in general constant for any given species.&nbsp; Thus in each cell of a human being there are 48 chromosomes (24 pairs)....&quot;&nbsp; [<em>Principles of Heredity</em>, 3rd. ed., by Laurence R. Snyder (1946), p. 26.]</font></strong><br>
      <br>
    </div>
	</td>
  </tr>
